					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>Montana Festival of the Book Begins and Sheeler Named NBA Finalist</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 10-22-08</p>
			
							<table width="25" align="right" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
					<tr>
						<td>&nbsp;</td>
						<td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/thumbnails_feature/Final_Poster_thumb.jpg" width="220" height="509" /></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>

					
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>
				</table>
			
							<p>The big news this week is the announcement that Colorado author and journalist<a target="_blank" href="http://web.mac.com/jsheeler/jimsheeler.com/jim_sheeler.html" title=" Jim Sheeler"> Jim Sheeler</a>&#8216;s <I>Final Salute: A Story of Unfinished Lives</I> is a <a target="_blank" href="http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/oct/15/final-salute-finalist-national-book-award/" title="finalist for the National Book Award">finalist for the National Book Award</a> in the nonfiction category.&nbsp; Sheeler previously won a Pulitzer Prize for <a target="_blank" href="http://www.rockymountainnews.com/special-reports/final-salute/" title="the articles">the articles</a> upon which the book is based.
</p>
<p>
The <a target="_blank" href="http://www.humanitiesmontana.org/BookFestival/bookfest.shtml" title="Montana Festival of the Book">Montana Festival of the Book</a> opens tomorrow in Missoula with a &#8220;Celebrity Define-A-Thon&#8221; to benefit the festival (Wilma Theatre, 7 p.m.).&nbsp; Missoula mayor Mayor John Engen and journalist Ian Marquand among others will participate in what organizers promise will be a &#8220;fun and cutthroat&#8221; event.
</p>
<p>
Friday and Saturday&#8217;s schedules are jam packed with readings, panels, film screenings and poetry slams.&nbsp; Many of the writers we&#8217;ve featured on NewWest.Net/Books will participate.&nbsp; 
</p>
<p>
Some highlights from Friday:
</p>
<p>
-Idaho writer Brandon Schrand will read with Alan Weltzien and Barbara Richard (1 p.m., Holiday Inn, Yellowstone/Glacier Rooms).&nbsp; Schrand&#8217;s <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/brandon_r_schrands_the_enders_hotel/C39/L39/" title="The Enders Hotel">The Enders Hotel</a></I> is an entertaining, insightful memoir of his childhood growing up in hotel in Soda Springs, Idaho.
</p>
<p>
-Novelists David Allen Cates and Mary Clearman Blew will read at 2:30 p.m. (Holiday Inn, Ballroom D.)  Here are our reviews of Cates&#8217; <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/rambling_man_david_allan_cates_freeman_walker/C39/L39/" title="Freeman Walker">Freeman Walker</a></I> and Blew&#8217;s <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/old_and_new_montana_clash_in_accomplished_jackalope_dreams/C39/L39/" title="Jackalope Dreams">Jackalope Dreams</a></I>, and <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_mary_clearman_blew/C39/L39/" title="an interview with Blew">an interview with Blew</a>.
</p>
<p>
-Also at 2:30, John Clayton will discuss his <I>Images of America: Red Lodge</I> (Holiday Inn, Yellowstone/Glacier Rooms).&nbsp; Clayton&#8217;s biography of Caroline Lockhart, <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/cowboys_were_her_weakness_john_claytons_ithe_cowboy_girl_i/C39/L39/" title="The Cowboy Girl">The Cowboy Girl</a></I>, was one of my favorite Wyoming books of last year.
</p>
<p>
Some highlights from Saturday:
</p>
<p>
-William Kittredge, Annick Smith, Mary Clearman Blew, and William Lang will speak about the twentieth anniversary of <I>Last Best Place</I>, an anthology of Montana literature (1 p.m., Holiday Inn Ballroom A/B).
</p>
<p>
-Also at one o&#8217;clock, Rafael Chac&#243;n will discuss his book <I>AJ Gibson: Original Man</I> (Holiday Inn, Yellowstone/Glacier Rooms).&nbsp; Brian D&#8217;Ambrosio&#8217;s <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/rafael_chacons_biography_of_montana_architect_aj_gibson/C39/L39/" title="review of the book is here">review of the book is here</a>.
</p>
<p>
-New West contributor Greg Lemon will participate on the panel &#8220;True Life: Writing Another&#8217;s Life Story,&#8221; at 4 p.m. (Holiday Inn Ballroom A/B).&nbsp; Here is <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_greg_lemon/C39/L39/" title="an interview with Lemon">an interview with Lemon</a> and <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/blue_man_in_a_red_state_an_excerpt/C39/L39/" title="an excerpt from his biography">an excerpt from his biography</a> of Montana Governor Brian Schweitzer.
</p>
<p>
-Also at four, a group of the University of Montana&#8217;s talented creative writing faculty will read (Holiday Inn, Three Rivers Room).&nbsp; Judy Blunt, Kevin Canty, Deborah Magpie Earling, Beverly Lowry, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_deirdre_mcnamer/C39/L39/" title="Deidre McNamer">Deidre McNamer</a> and Robert Stubblefield will participate.&nbsp; McNamer&#8217;s <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/deidre_mcnamers_red_rover/C39/L39/" title="Red Rover">Red Rover</a></I> was one of my favorite books of last year.
</p>
<p>
-The Gala Reading at the Wilma Theatre (7:30 p.m.) will feature Rick Bass (whose <I>Why I Came West</I> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/montanas_jeremiah_rick_basss_why_i_came_west/C39/L39/" title="I reviewed recently">I reviewed recently</a>), Kim Barnes (my <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_kim_barnes_part_one/C39/L39/" title="interview">interview</a> and review of her new novel <I>A Country Called Home</I> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/gone_fishing_kim_barnes_a_country_called_home/C39/L39/" title="is here">is here</a>), and Thomas McGuane (whose crackerjack story collection <I>Gallatin Canyon</I> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/main/article/thomas_mcguanes_gallatin_canyon/" title="I reviewed last year">I reviewed last year</a>).
</p>
<p>
Finally, I&#8217;ve previously mentioned the entertaining blog of the Boulder Book Store&#8217;s head buyer, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/boulder_book_stores_buyer_blogs_columnist_arouses_ire_and_vegas_gets_the_li/C39/L39/" title="Arsen Kashkashian">Arsen Kashkashian</a>, and wanted to point out his informative <a target="_blank" href="http://kashsbookcorner.blogspot.com/" title="post from last week">post from last week</a>.&nbsp; The Boulder Book Store recently celebrated its 35th anniversary, and as a part of that brought several bestselling writers to town. Kashkashian analyzes three of those recent events, and discusses what went wrong and what went right.&nbsp; The Neil Gaiman reading hosted at the Unity Church was a huge hit, selling out the 600-seat venue (with $6 tickets), and the Book Store sold 285 copies of the book Gaiman was promoting, as well as &#8220;dozens of backlist books.&#8221; Kashkashian reports that a live screening of a Phillip Roth interview was a bust, however, as was a Philippa Gregory reading that they had to cancel due to lack of ticket sales.
</p>
<p>
Have some regional literary news or events to share?&nbsp; If so,  <script type="text/javascript">
